  <h1>Hospital Financial Assistance Programs</h1>
  <p><em>Reviewed by Aspen Lockwood (AL), Editor-in-Chief. Updated May 2026.</em></p>
  <h2>ACA requirements for nonprofit hospitals</h2><p>Section 501(r) of the Internal Revenue Code requires nonprofit hospitals to: maintain a written financial assistance policy (FAP); limit charges to FAP-eligible patients to amounts generally billed to insurers; not take extraordinary collection actions before determining FAP eligibility; and widely publicize the FAP. For-profit hospitals have no federal financial assistance requirement but may have voluntary programs.</p>
  <h2>Typical income thresholds</h2><p>Most nonprofit hospitals provide: 100% free care for incomes up to 200% of the federal poverty level ($30,120 for a single person in 2026); sliding-scale discounts for incomes up to 300–400% of FPL. Some large health systems (Kaiser, Mayo, UCSF) extend discounts to 500–600% of FPL.</p>
  <h2>How to apply</h2><p>Request the FAP application from the billing department or download it from the hospital website (required to be publicly posted). Submit with: recent tax return, 2–3 months of pay stubs, bank statements, and a completed application. Hospitals must make a determination within a reasonable time — typically 2–6 weeks.</p>
  <h2>If denied</h2><p>Request a written explanation. You can appeal. If you believe the hospital is violating its FAP or Section 501(r), file a complaint with the IRS (Form 13909) or your state&rsquo;s hospital licensing authority.</p>
  <h2>Where to go from here</h2>
  <p>See <a href="/guides/how-to-negotiate-hospital-bills">how to negotiate bills</a> and <a href="/guides/medical-billing-errors">finding billing errors</a>.</p>
